Define a function to locate the root that serves as the starting point of the trajectory. This function was borrowed from the monocle3 tutorial. I am setting the early group as the chemo-naive in order to map the progression to the exhausted state post-chemotherapy.

In[10]:
# Monocle3 method for calculating the root principal node
get_root_principal_node <- function(cds, early_group) {
  cell_ids <- which(colData(cds)$treatment_stage == early_group)
  
  closest_vertex <- cds@principal_graph_aux[['UMAP']]$pr_graph_cell_proj_closest_vertex
  closest_vertex <- as.matrix(closest_vertex[colnames(cds), ])
  
  root <- igraph::V(principal_graph(cds)[['UMAP']])$name[
    as.numeric(names(which.max(table(closest_vertex[cell_ids,]))))
  ]
  return(root)
}

The article mentions IFNG as a marker for cytotoxicity. I'm locating the cell with the highest expression of this gene and using it as the root cell to build the trajectory.

In[]:
# Calculate the root cell using IFNG expression
ifng_values <- Matrix::as.matrix(exprs(cds)['IFNG', ])
ifng_values <- as.data.frame(ifng_values)
setDT(ifng_values, keep.rownames=TRUE)
setorder(ifng_values, -V1)

Calculate pseudotime and visualize. Here I'm comparing two different methods of choosing the root node. On the left is the method provided by Monocle3 authors which is oddly showing pseudotime in reverse where cells from IDS samples are at the start. Using the cell with the highest expression of IFNG, a marker for T cell cytotoxicity, returns pseudotime in the expected direction. I'm choosing to proceed with the version on the right.

In[12]:

Here, I'm performing a quick logisitic regression where pseudotime is the predictor and treatment stage is the outcome. This will statistically validate that pseudotime is measuring the change between treatment stages and direction. Results show the odds of a cell being IDS increase by ~1.08% for every unit increase in pseudotime.

In[13]:
x <- data.frame(pseudotime=pseudotime(cds), treatment_stage=colData(cds)$treatment_stage)

x <- x[is.finite(x$pseudotime), ]
x$treatment_stage <- factor(x$treatment_stage, levels=c('chemo-naive', 'IDS'))

model <- glm(treatment_stage ~ pseudotime, data=x, family=binomial)

summary(model)

Visualize the results of the Logistic Regression - Probability of a cell being in the IDS group goes up as pseudotime increases.

In[]:
pred <- predict(model, newdata=x, type='link', se.fit=TRUE)
x$fit <- pred$fit
x$se.fit <- pred$se.fit

x$predicted <- plogis(x$fit)
x$lower <- plogis(x$fit - 1.96 * x$se.fit)
x$upper <- plogis(x$fit + 1.96 * x$se.fit)

# Visualize the results

  geom_line(color='blue', size=1) +

  labs(x='Pseudotime', y='Probability of IDS',

  theme_bw()

Fit GLM for each gene as a function of pseudotime to find genes that vary along the trajectory. Genes increasing with pseudotime should be markers for exhausted T cells post-chemotherapy. I will plot the top 6 with the most significant q-values and largest normalized effect scores.

In[14]:
pseudotime_effects <- cds %>% 
                fit_models(model_formula_str='~pseudotime') %>% coefficient_table() %>% 
                filter(term == 'pseudotime' & q_value < 0.05) %>% arrange(q_value) %>% 

                as.data.table()

setorder(pseudotime_effects, q_value, -normalized_effect)
top_genes <- pseudotime_effects[1:6][, gene_id]

In[16]:
cds_subset <- cds[rownames(rowData(cds)) %in% top_genes, ]
rowData(cds_subset)$gene_short_name <- rownames(rowData(cds_subset))

It looks like 5 of the top 6 genes are downregulated as cells progress from a chemo-naive to exhausted state. What's interesting is increased expression of IL7R as cells transition out of the cytotoxic state. A quick literature search shows that decreased expression of IL7R is associated with exhausted T cells. However, some articles point to a more "stem-like" population of T cells that retains expression of IL7R which is correlated with survival and self-renewal. This analysis could be extended further by using pseudotime to predict functional relationships, identifying potential targets.

https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7049579/
https://jitc.bmj.com/content/jitc/10/Suppl_2/A861.full.pdf
